CS166 Problem Set 2: Image Processing

Instructions

  • This problem set is due on Friday, April 26th at 10AM.

  • Please abide by the collaboration policy on the Canvas page.

  • To hand in your work, upload a ZIP archive to Gradescope containing

    • a document called report.pdf with your name, your solutions, and the amount of time it took you to complete the assignment,
    • the images used in your answers, named as specified by the questions, and
    • a file called solve.py, or a directory called solve containing a __main__.py file, that generates them.

  • Your solution script/module will be executed with a Python 3.10.14 interpreter with access to numpy 1.26.4 and Pillow 10.3.0. The problem set files will be accessible as ../ps2/<filename>.

  • Use NumPys save and load functions to write/read .npy and .npz files.

  • Unless otherwise specified, perform all operations in a linear luminance regime. When reading PNG images, scale to the range [0, 1] and gamma-decode. When writing them, gamma-encode, scale to the range [0, 256), and quantize. The read_image and write_image functions in the provided problem set library take care of this for you.

Questions

  1. Cross-correlation (15%): Implement cross-correlation, nearest-neighbor-padding so the output is the same size as the input (see ps_lib.pad). Your implementation can assume the kernel height and kernel width are odd. For this question, dont use pre-written convolution functions from NumPy. Cross-correlate apple.png with the provided Gaussian and Sobel kernels. Save the results as q1-gaussian.png, q1-sobel-vertical.png, and q1-sobel-horizontal.png, and include them in your report. (Note: Convolution and cross-correlation are equivalent with symmetrical kernels.)

  2. Image pyramids (15%): Make Laplacian pyramids from apple.png and orange.png, using the Gaussian kernel provided. Downsample by a factor of 2 at each level, via bicubic interpolation (you can use the resize function defined in the problem set library). Additionally, make a Gaussian pyramid from mask.png. Save the pyramids as q2-apple.npy, q2-orange.npy, and q2-mask.npy. Each pyramid should be an array (dtype: object) of height width float32 arrays of increasing size. Continue downsampling until you generate an image with a height or width less than the kernels. Select a reasonable dynamic range for each pyramid level, render the pyramids as q2-apple-1.png, q2-apple-2.png, etc., and include these renderings in your report.

  3. Blending (15%): Use mask.png to generate the Laplacian pyramid blend of apple.png and orange.png. Save it as q3-apple-and-orange.png and include it in your report. Repeat this process on your own image/mask set (either take pictures or find them online). Save the result as q3-new-images.png and include it in your report.

  4. Using the PiCam (10%): Take four pictures of the same scene with the Raspberry Pi camera using the capture-image script provided in Problem Set 1, with mode RGB. Use different exposure durations and/or gain factors for each image. Save these images as q4-shot-1.npz q4-shot-4.npz. Select reasonable dynamic ranges for the images, render them as q4-shot-1.png q4-shot-4.png, and include them in your report.

  5. HDR imaging (15%): Combine canyon-shot-1.png canyon-shot-4.png into a single high-dynamic-range image, q5-canyon-composite.npy, a float32 array using the brightness scale from the darkest image (shot 1). To merge the shots, compare nonsaturated pixels across images to compute the relative gain factors. Render the composite image at five brightness/contrast levels, q5-canyon-rendering-1.png q5-canyon-rendering-5.png, and include them in your report. Point out details visible in some renderings but not others (13 sentences). Repeat this process for the images you captured in question 4, replacing canyon with captured in the filenames. NumPys quantile function can be useful when selecting brightness/contrast levels.

  6. Bilateral filtering (15%): Implement bilateral filtering, defined for a pixel (y,x)(y, x)(y,x)

    bila(y,x)=1ky,xG(yy,xx;domain)G(I(y,x)I(y,x);range)I(y,x), \textrm{bila}(y,x) = { \frac{1}{k} \sum_{y', x'} G(y-y', x-x'; \sigma_\text{domain})\, G(\|I(y, x)-I(y', x')\|; \sigma_\text{range})\, I(y', x') }\text{,} bila(y,x)=k1y,xG(yy,xx;domain)G(I(y,x)I(y,x);range)I(y,x),

    where III is the input image, GGG is the Gaussian function, and kkk is a normalization factor defined

    k=y,xG(yy,xx;domain)G(I(y,x)I(y,x);range). k = { \sum_{y', x'} G(y-y', x-x'; \sigma_\text{domain})\, G(\|I(y, x)-I(y', x')\|; \sigma_\text{range}) }\text{.} k=y,xG(yy,xx;domain)G(I(y,x)I(y,x);range).

    The range Gaussian on I(y,x)I(y,x)\|I(y, x)-I(y', x')\|I(y,x)I(y,x) should be computed using Euclidean distances in RGB, assuming a dynamic range of [0, 1]. Try your filter on noisy-image.png, with domain=1\sigma_\text{domain}=1domain=1 and range=0.3\sigma_\text{range}=0.3range=0.3. Save the result as q6-filtered-image.png and include it in your report. How does changing the \sigma values change the result (12 sentences)?

  7. Tone mapping (15%): Perform tone mapping on the HDR canyon image, following these steps:

    • Decompose your image into luminance and chrominance channels. The luminance channel is the YYY channel you computed in your answer to Problem Set 1, Question 6, plus a small constant, to avoid problems at

      1. The chrominance image is the original image, divided by the luminance.

    • Convert the luminance channel to a log10 scale.

    • Generate the base image from the log10 luminance image using bilateral filtering, with domain=image_width/50\sigma_\text{domain}=\texttt{image\_width}/50domain=image_width/50 and range=0.4\sigma_\text{range}=0.4range=0.4.

    • Compute the detail image, subtracting the base from the original log-scale image.

    • Compute the scale factor base\alpha_\text{base}base in the log domain that brings the dynamic range (<highest value>/<lowest nonzero value>) of the base to the target dynamic range, Rtarget=100R_\text{target}=100Rtarget=100 (in the linear regime). Then, compute the offset \beta such that the highest base value is 1 once mapped back to the linear domain.

    • Merge the transformed base and the amplified details in the log domain to construct the new luminance channel:

      Loutput=baseLbase+detailLdetail+, L_\text{output} = { \alpha_\text{base} L_\text{base} + \alpha_\text{detail} L_\text{detail} + \beta }\text{,} Loutput=baseLbase+detailLdetail+,

      with detail=3\alpha_\text{detail}=3detail=3.

    • Transform back to a linear scale and merge the processed luminance channel with the chrominance channels.

    Save the result as q7-canyon.png and include it in your report. Repeat this process using q5-captured-composite.npy, generating q7-captured.png.
